We can add the two fractions by finding a common denominator, rewriting each fraction so both have the common denominator, then adding them together.

First, we need to find a common denominator. A common multiple of $2$ and $3$ is $6$.

We can rewrite both fractions to have $6$ as their denominators:

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{x}{2}\blueD{\times\dfrac33}&=\dfrac{3x}{6} \\\\
\dfrac{y}{3}\blueD{\times\dfrac22}&=\dfrac{2y}{6}
\end{align}$

Now, we can add the fractions:

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{x}{2}+\dfrac{y}{3}&=\dfrac{3x}{6}+\dfrac{2y}{6} \\\\
&=\dfrac{3x+2y}{6}
\end{align}$

**$\dfrac{3x+2y}{6}$ is equivalent to $\dfrac{x}{2}+\dfrac{y}{3}$.**
